Because each time, the OR can only add bits, so the number of possible OR values is at most log(max_value), which for binary numbers up to 1e6 bits is manageable. Wait, the maximum possible OR is a number with up to n bits. So for n=1e6, this is not feasible. Hmm, but perhaps the number of distinct OR values for each position is small. Let me think of the process: 

Initialize a set for each position. At position 0, the only substring is s[0], so the OR is s[0]. At position 1, the substrings ending at 1 are s[0..1] and s[1]. The ORs are (s[0] | s[1]), and s[1]. But the set for position 1 is { (prev ORs | s[1]), s[1] } 

Wait, but the previous ORs are the ORs of substrings ending at 0. So for each position i, the new ORs are the OR of the previous ORs (from i-1) with the current bit, plus the current bit itself. The total OR is the OR of all these values. Wait, but the total OR is the OR of all possible substrings. Alternatively, the total OR can be computed incrementally.
